		<h1> Introduction to Abstraction </h1>
	</div>
	<div class = "concept">
	   <h2 class = "concept-title"> Program with object </h2>
	   <div class = "concept-description">
	<p> Python has been an object-oriented language since it was developed. Because of this, creating and using classes and objects are  easy. An object-oriented program is based on classes and there exists a collection of interacting objects, as opposed to the conventional model, in which a program consists of functions and routines. In object-oriented programmming (OOP), each object can receive messages, process data, and send messages to other objects. </p>
	<p> Objects are key to understanding object-oriented technology. Look around right now and you'll find many examples of real-world objects: your dog, your desk, your television set, your bicycle. Software objects are conceptually similar to real-world objects: they too consist of state and related behavior. An object stores its state in fields (variables in some programming languages) and exposes its behavior through methods (functions in some programming languages). Methods operate on an object's internal state and serve as the primary mechanism for object-to-object communication.
	</div></div>
	   
	<div class = "concept">
	   <h2 class = "concept-title"> Use Functions </h2>
	   <div class = "concept-description">
       <p> A function is a named container for a block of code.   If functions are groups of code, then modules are groups of functions. We can write some program with using function and modules.To use modules, we can use either the import or the from keyword. import is the simplest and most common keyword. There are plenty of built in modules, e.g. webbrowser, time,   os (operating system) etc.</p>
       <p>* The webbrowser module includes functions to open URLs in interactive browser applications. To open a page in the browser, use the open() function. The webbrowser function takes in the link that you want to open and puts that link in quotes. When a module is first imported, Python searches for the module and if found, it creates a module object , initializing it.</p>
       
       <p>* Time module provides various time-related functions. Time module provides functions for working with times and for converting between representations. e.g. time.sleep(secs), time.ctime([sec]) etc. time.sleep(secs) which suspends the program for a given numbers of seconds. time.ctime() shows current time on your computer. If secs is not provided or None, the current time as returned by time() is used. </p>
<p> Suppose, we want to write a program that says take a break after every hour to a somebody whose sits and works for long time. </P>
	<p><b> import time<br>
import webbrowser<br>
<br>
total_breaks = 3  # no. of breaks in whole day <br>
break_count = 0<br>
<br>
while(break_count < total_breaks):<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;    time.sleep(10) # time in seconds <br>  
 &nbsp; &nbsp;  webbrowser.open("https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0KSOMA3QBU0")<br>
 &nbsp; &nbsp;  break_count = break_count + 1</b> </p>
	<p> We don't know how functions open files from webbrowser,  or how the sleep function suspends the program for seconds. All those things are hidden from us and that hiding of details in programming is called <em>abstraction</em>. The idea of abstraction is really powerful in programming, because it allows us to focus on the program that we actually want to write, and it empowers us to use these functions simply by reading their documentations. </p>
	<p> So, much like webbrowser and time, Python has another module inside it called os, which is short for operating system. Inside os are several functions. Two of them are listdir, which lists out all the files in a given directory, and rename, which renames a given file.</p> 
	<p> TO LEARN MORE ABOUT PYTHON DOCUMENTATIONS : <a href = "https://docs.python.org/2.7/library/index.html"> click here </a> </p>
	<p> In some cases, functions won't quite present a very eloquent solution. Functions are great to use when data is central to the work being done. Classes are great when you need to represent a collection of attributes and methods that will be used over and over again in other places. Classes are a way to organize your code into generic, reusable pieces. At their best, they are generic blueprints for things that will be used over and over again with little modification.</p>
	
	   </div></div>
	<div class = "concept">
	   <h2 class = "concept-title"> Use Classes: Draw Turtles </h2>
	   <div class = "concept-description">
	<p>  Turtle graphics is a popular way for introducing programming to kids. It was part of the original Logo programming language. Turtle is like a drawing board. It has functions like turtle.forward(...) and turtle.left(...) which can move the turtle around. </p>
	<p> Python has a library called turtle that is part of the standard python installation. To use it, you need only type:
from turtle import * or import turtle<br>
You can type this right in the python interpreter to experiment with turtle graphics or, better yet, include this line at the top of your program and then use turtle drawing commands in your program! In the turtle package when you run a program with turtle commands, a special window will open where the drawing will take place.</p>
	<p> There is a module in Python called turtle with a lowercase t. The turtle module provides turtle graphics primitives, in both object-oriented and procedure-oriented ways. A class Turtle with an uppercase T. A class as a neatly packaged box, that puts things together really well. And it allows us to write code like turtle.Turtle(), which is calling a function __init__. init stands for initialize, and what it does is it creates space in memory for a new instance or a new object of the class Turtle. This instance we called brad. Brad can now acces all of the rest of the methods that are inside class Turtle like forward, left,right.</p>
<p><b>1.&nbsp;import turtle &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;# Allows us to use turtles<br>
<br>
def draw_shape():<br>
 2.&nbsp;&nbsp;wn = turtle.Screen() &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;     # Creates a playground for turtles<br>
 3.&nbsp;&nbsp;brad = turtle.Turtle()&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;    # Create a turtle, assign to brad<br>

 4.&nbsp;&nbsp;brad.forward(50) &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;         # Tell brad to move forward by 50 units<br>
5.&nbsp;&nbsp;brad.left(90)   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;          # Tell brad to turn by 90 degrees<br>
<br>
6.&nbsp;wn.exitonclick() &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;            # Wait for user to close window<br>
<br>
draw_shape()</b></p>
<p> Here are a couple of things we will need to understand about this program.<br>

The first line tells Python to load a module named turtle. That module brings us two new types that we can use: the Turtle type, and the Screen type. The dot notation turtle.Turtle means "The Turtle type that is defined within the turtle module" (Remember that Python is case sensitive, so the module name, with a lowercase t, is different from the type Turtle.)<br>

We then create and open what it calls a screen (we would prefer to call it a window), which we assign to variable wn. Every window contains a canvas, which is the area inside the window on which we can draw.<br>

In line 3 we create a turtle. The variable brad is made to refer to this turtle.<br>

So these first three lines have set things up, we are ready to get our turtle to draw on our canvas.<br>

In lines 4-5, we instruct the object brad to move, and to turn. We do this by invoking, or activating, brad's methods : these are the instructions that all turtles know how to respond to.

The line 6 plays a part too:  it enters a state where it waits for events (like keypresses, or mouse movement and clicks). The program will terminate when the user closes the window. And Last line calling the function that draw shape.</p>

	</div></div>
