	   <h2 class = "concept-title"> Use Classes: Profanity Editor </h2>
	   <div class = "concept-description">
	<p> How to detects curse words in a text or the draft of an email or an article? Firstly, you will have to read text from document and secondly, check this text for curse words.</p>
	<p> To read text from document, there is function in Python called open, which allows you to work with files on your computer. This function takes in the address or the location of the file you wnat to open. The Python interpreter has a number of functions built into it that are always available. Here is a list of  <a href = "https://docs.python.org/2/library/functions.html">  Built-in-Functions </a>
<p><b>1. import urllib<br>2. def read_text():<br>
3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; quotes = open(" ") &nbsp; # location of the file <br>
4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; contents_of_the_file = quotes.read() &nbsp; # allows read the contents of file <br>
5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; quotes.close() <br>

6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; check_profanity(contents_of_file)<br></b> </p>
	<p> In above program, we did not import anything in our code for open function. In Python Documentation, it says that open function opens a file, returns an object of the file type. In second line, when we wrote quotes = open(file_location)--> quotes is an object or an instance of the file. Eventhough, there is no class involved, the code for open was actually implemented inside Python and calling some init-like function to create an object of file.</p>
	<p> Next, how can we check that there is a curse word in our text? There is a module in Python called, URL lib, which helps us get information from the internet. It has a function called, URL open, which takes in a link to a website. The function URL open, help us make a connection, to the website which is given by us for profanity check. So, much like webbrowser,time and OS, urllib is also a module or a file in Python. And urlopen is a function inside urllib module. This module provides a high-level interface for fetching data across the World Wide Web. In particular, the urlopen() function is similar to the built-in function open(), but accepts Universal Resource Locators (URLs) instead of filenames.</p>
	<p> <b> 7.&nbsp; def check_profanity(text_to_check):<br>
8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; connection = urllib.urlopen(" " + text_to_check)&nbsp;# "website that check profanity" <br>
9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; output = connection.read()<br>
10.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;connection.close()<br>
11.&nbsp;read_text()<br></b></p>
